<header class="header">
  <h1>How Many Frost-Free Days Do Potatoes Need?</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Potatoes tolerate cool weather — but maturity still has a deadline.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, first frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> defines a practical seasonal boundary.
    Potatoes are more cold-tolerant than warm-season crops, but how well they finish still depends on
    how many frost-free days (and how much heat) you have before frost risk returns.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Start With Your Frost Window (The Planning Boundary)</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate uses 1991–2020 climate normals and frames frost timing at the
    <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your listed frost dates represent typical-year boundaries — not guarantees.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate your local frost-free window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For fall planning specifically, your typical first frost date is the key boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How Many Frost-Free Days Do Potatoes Typically Need?</h2>

  <p>
    Potato maturity varies by variety and intended harvest stage, but typical planning ranges are:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>New potatoes (early harvest):</strong> often ~60–80 days after planting</li>
    <li><strong>Mid-season potatoes:</strong> often ~80–100 days</li>
    <li><strong>Late/maincrop potatoes (storage types):</strong> often ~100–120+ days</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In a short growing season, those ranges matter because a late variety may not fully finish before frost risk returns.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why “Days” Still Isn’t the Full Story</h2>

  <p>
    Potatoes tolerate cool temperatures better than tomatoes or peppers,
    but growth rate still responds to temperature.
  </p>

  <p>
    Late-season cooling can slow bulking even when frost hasn’t occurred yet.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the same planning problem described in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>:
    development is not purely a calendar function.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, the best way to evaluate risk is to combine frost timing with heat accumulation.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Using Growing Degree Days to Understand Maturity Margin</h2>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days (GDD) measure accumulated heat over time.
    Many warm-season crops are modeled with a base of 50°F, but the key takeaway is broader:
    <strong>cool seasons accumulate heat more slowly</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your late season is mild and cooling quickly, potato bulking may slow before your frost boundary.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate your seasonal heat budget using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For how this fits into the overall system, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When Potatoes Fit Comfortably in a Short Season</h2>

  <p>
    Potatoes are more likely to fit comfortably if:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>You choose early or mid-season varieties.</li>
    <li>Your frost-free window comfortably exceeds the variety’s maturity range.</li>
    <li>Your climate maintains enough late-season warmth for continued bulking.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short climates, early potatoes often provide the most reliable outcomes in a typical year.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When Potatoes Become Higher Risk</h2>

  <p>
    Potatoes are higher risk if:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>You select late/maincrop varieties in a very short frost-free window.</li>
    <li>Late-season temperatures cool quickly, slowing bulking.</li>
    <li>Your plan depends on a narrow margin between maturity range and first frost boundary.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In those scenarios, potatoes may still produce a harvest — but may not reach full size or storage maturity before the season ends.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Improving Your Margin</h2>

  <p>
    In constrained seasons, margin improvements usually come from time leverage:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Planting promptly once conditions allow</li>
    <li>Selecting earlier varieties</li>
    <li>Using favorable microclimates to reduce early fall frost exposure</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If you’re sequencing multiple crops around frost boundaries, you can coordinate timing using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    Potatoes are typically direct-planted, but the planner can still help structure the overall frost-based schedule across crops.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Potato Timing Model</h2>

  <p>
    To evaluate potato feasibility in your climate, follow this chain:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Frost-Free Days → Variety Maturity Range → Seasonal Heat (GDD) → Risk Margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    When your frost-free window and seasonal warmth align with variety timing,
    potatoes can finish reliably in a typical year.
  </p>

  <p>
    When they don’t, variety selection is usually the most effective fix.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Potatoes often need ~60–120+ days depending on variety and harvest stage.</li>
    <li>Frost dates use a 32°F definition and 50% probability framing.</li>
    <li>Cool late seasons can slow bulking even before frost occurs.</li>
    <li>Early and mid-season varieties improve reliability in short climates.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short growing seasons, potato success comes from matching variety timing
    to your frost-free window — with enough buffer for typical variation.
  </p>
</section>